 of Stiegler's philosophy and demonstrates that this theory of the political decision highlights the difficulties that contemporary political ontology faces when addressing global and large-scale political problems. The book provides an overview of Stiegler's philosophy useful for those unfamiliar with his thought, shows how he draws on key influences including Deleuze, Derrida, Freud, and Simondon to develop his conception of judgment, and considers the challenges and consequences of his embrace of totalizing political decisions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aOntologyxPolitical aspects. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Critical Theory. 4aPhilosophy : Post Structuralism. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Theory. 4aSociology : Social Theory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849204940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438492049423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438492049/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles